# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: embryophyte
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The **ABC model of flower development** is a scientific model of the process by which flowering plants produce a pattern of gene expression in meristems that leads to the appearance of an organ oriented towards sexual reproduction, a flower.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The latter phase has been modelled using the **ABC model**, which aims to describe the biological basis of the process from the perspective of molecular and developmental genetics.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] An external stimulus is required in order to trigger the differentiation of the meristem into a flower meristem.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This stimulus will activate mitotic cell division in the apical meristem, particularly on its sides where new primordia are formed.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This same stimulus will also cause the meristem to follow a developmental pattern that will lead to the growth of floral meristems as opposed to vegetative meristems.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The main difference between these two types of meristem, apart from the obvious disparity between the objective organ, is the verticillate (or whorled) phyllotaxis, that is, the absence of stem elongation among the successive whorls or verticils of the primordium.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] These verticils follow an acropetal development, giving rise to sepals, petals, stamens and carpels.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Another difference from vegetative axillary meristems is that the floral meristem is "determined", which means that, once differentiated, its cells will no longer divide.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The identity of the organs present in the four floral verticils is a consequence of the interaction of at least three types of gene products, each with distinct functions.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] According to the ABC model, functions A and C are required in order to determine the identity of the verticils of the perianth and the reproductive verticils, respectively.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] These functions are exclusive and the absence of one of them means that the other will determine the identity of all the floral verticils.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B function allows the differentiation of petals from sepals in the secondary verticil, as well as the differentiation of the stamen from the carpel on the tertiary verticil.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Goethe's **foliar theory** was formulated in the 18th century and it suggests that the constituent parts of a flower are structurally modified leaves, which are functionally specialized for reproduction or protection.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The transition from the vegetative phase to a reproductive phase involves a dramatic change in the plant's vital cycle, perhaps the most important one, as the process must be carried out correctly in order to guarantee that the plant produces descendants.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This transition is characterised by the induction and development of the meristem of the inflorescence, which will produce a collection of flowers or one flower.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This morphogenetic change contains both endogenous and exogenous elements: For example, in order for the change to be initiated the plant must have a certain number of leaves and contain a certain level of total biomass.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Certain environmental conditions are also required such as a characteristic photoperiod.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Plant hormones play an important part in the process, with the gibberellins having a particularly important role.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are many signals that regulate the molecular biology of the process.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The following three genes in *Arabidopsis thaliana* possess both common and independent functions in floral transition: *FLOWERING LOCUS T* (*FT*), *LEAFY* (*LFY*), *SUPPRESSOR OF OVEREXPRESSION OF CONSTANS1* (*SOC1*, also called *AGAMOUS-LIKE20*).
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] *SOC1* is a MADS-box-type gene, which integrates responses to photoperiod, vernalization and gibberellins.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The meristem can be defined as the tissue or group of plant tissues that contain undifferentiated stem cells, which are capable of producing any type of cell tissue.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Their maintenance and development, both in the vegetative meristem or the meristem of the inflorescence is controlled by genetic cell fate determination mechanisms.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that a number of genes will directly regulate, for example, the maintenance of the stem cell's characteristics (gene *WUSCHEL* or *WUS*), and others will act via negative feedback mechanisms in order to inhibit a characteristic (gene *CLAVATA* or *CLV*).
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this way both mechanisms give rise to a feedback loop, which along with other elements lend a great deal of robustness to the system.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Along with the *WUS* gene the *SHOOTMERISTEMLESS* (*STM*) gene also represses the differentiation of the meristematic dome.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This gene acts by inhibiting the possible differentiation of the stem cells but still allows cell division in the daughter cells, which, had they been allowed to differentiate, would have given rise to distinct organs.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] A flower's anatomy, as defined by the presence of a series of organs (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels) positioned according to a given pattern, facilitate sexual reproduction in flowering plants.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model of flower development was first formulated by George Haughn and Chris Somerville in 1988.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was first used as a model to describe the collection of genetic mechanisms that establish floral organ identity in the Rosids, as exemplified by *Arabidopsis thaliana*, and the Asterids, as demonstrated by *Antirrhinum majus*.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both species have four verticils (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels), which are defined by the differential expression of a number of homeotic genes present in each verticil.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that the sepals are solely characterized by the expression of A genes, while the petals are characterized by the co-expression of A and B genes.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B and C genes establish the identity of the stamens and the carpels only require C genes to be active.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Type A and C genes are reciprocally antagonistic.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The fact that these homeotic genes determine an organ's identity becomes evident when a gene that represents a particular function, for example the A gene, is not expressed.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* this loss results in a flower which is composed of one verticil of carpels, another containing stamens and another of carpels.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This method for studying gene function uses reverse genetics techniques to produce transgenic plants that contain a mechanism for gene silencing through RNA interference.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In other studies, using forward genetics techniques such as genetic mapping, it is the analysis of the phenotypes of flowers with structural anomalies that leads to the cloning of the gene of interest.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The flowers may possess a non-functional or over expressed allele for the gene being studied.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The existence of two supplementary functions, D and E, have also been proposed in addition to the A, B and C functions already discussed.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function D specifies the identity of the ovule, as a separate reproductive function from the development of the carpels, which occurs after their determination.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function E relates to a physiological requirement that is a characteristic of all floral verticils, although, it was initially described as necessary for the development of the three innermost verticils (Function E *sensu stricto*).
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, its broader definition (*sensu lato*) suggests that it is required in the four verticils.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The gene products of genes with D and E functions are also MADS-box genes.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The methodology for studying flower development involves two steps.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Firstly, the identification of the exact genes required for determining the identity of the floral meristem.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* these include APETALA1 (*AP1*) and LEAFY (*LFY*).
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Secondly, genetic analysis is carried out on the aberrant phenotypes for the relative characteristics of the flowers, which allows the characterization of the homeotic genes implicated in the process.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are a great many mutations that affect floral morphology, although the analysis of these mutants is a recent development.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Supporting evidence for the existence of these mutations comes from the fact that a large number affect the identity of floral organs.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] For example, some organs develop in a location where others should develop.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is called homeotic mutation, which is analogous to HOX gene mutations found in *Drosophila*.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* and *Antirrhinum*, the two taxa on which models are based, these mutations always affect adjacent verticils.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Cloning studies have been carried out on DNA in the genes associated with the affected homeotic functions in the mutants discussed above.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] These studies used serial analysis of gene expression throughout floral development to show patterns of tissue expression, which, in general, correspond with the predictions of the ABC model.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The nature of these genes corresponds to that of transcription factors, which, as expected, have analogous structures to a group of factors contained in yeasts and animal cells.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This group is called MADS, which is an acronym for the different factors contained in the group.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] These MADS factors have been detected in all the vegetable species studied, although the involvement of other elements involved in the regulation of gene expression cannot be discounted.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, function A is mainly represented by two genes *APETALA1* (*AP1)* and *APETALA2* (*AP2*) *AP1* is a MADS-box type gene, while *AP2* belongs to the family of genes that contains AP2, which it gives its name to and which consists of transcription factors that are only found in plants.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] AP2 has also been shown to complex with the co-repressor TOPLESS (TPL) in developing floral buds to repress the C-class gene *AGAMOUS* (*AG*).
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] *AP2* not only functions in the first two verticils, but also in the remaining two, in developing ovules and even in leaves.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] It is also likely that post-transcriptional regulation exists, which controls its A function, or even that it has other purposes in the determination of organ identity independent of that mentioned here.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Antirrhinum*, the orthologous gene to *AP1* is *SQUAMOSA* (*SQUA*), which also has a particular impact on the floral meristem.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs for *AP2* are *LIPLESS1* (*LIP1*) and *LIPLESS2* (*LIP2*), which have a redundant function and are of special interest in the development of sepals, petals and ovules.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] A total of three genes have been isolated from *Petunia hybrida* that are similar to *AP2*: *P. hybrida APETALA2A* (*PhAP2A*), *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] *PhAP2A* is, to a large degree, homologous with the *AP2* gene of *Arabidopsis*, both in its sequence and in its expression pattern, which suggests that the two genes are orthologs.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The proteins *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*, on the other hand, are slightly different, even though they belong to the family of transcription factors that are similar to *AP2*.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition they are expressed in different ways, although they are very similar in comparison with *PhAP2A*.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In fact, the mutants for these genes do not show the usual phenotype, that of the null alleles of A genes.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* the type-B function mainly arises from two genes, *APETALA3* (*AP3*) and *PISTILLATA* (*PI*), both of which are MADS-box genes.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] A mutation of either of these genes causes the homeotic conversion of petals into sepals and of stamens into carpels.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This also occurs in its orthologs in *A. majus*, which are DEFICIENS (*DEF*) and *GLOBOSA* (*GLO*) respectively.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] For both species the active form of binding with DNA is that derived from the heterodimer: AP3 and PI, or DEF and GLO, dimerize.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is the form in which they are able to function.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *GLO*/*PI* lines that have been duplicated in *Petunia* contain *P. hybrida GLOBOSA1* (*PhGLO1*, also called *FBP1*) and also *PhGLO2* (also called *PMADS2* or *FBP3*).
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] For the functional elements equivalent to *AP3*/*DEF* in *Petunia* there is both a gene that possesses a relatively similar sequence, called *PhDEF* and there is also an atypical B function gene called PhTM6.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic studies have placed the first three within the «euAP3» lineage, while PhTM6 belongs to that of «paleoAP3».
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] As discussed above, the floral organs of eudicotyledonous angiosperms are arranged in 4 different verticils, containing the sepals, petals, stamen and carpels.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model states that the identity of these organs is determined by the homeotic genes A, A+B, B+C and C, respectively.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In contrast with the sepal and petal verticils of the eudicots, the perigone of many plants of the family Liliaceae have two nearly identical external petaloid verticils (the tepals).
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In order to explain the floral morphology of the Liliaceae, van Tunen *et al.* proposed a modified ABC model in 1993.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This model suggests that class B genes are not only expressed in verticils 2 and 3, but also in 1.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] It therefore follows that the organs of verticils 1 and 2 express class A and B genes and this is how they have a petaloid structure.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] This theoretical model has been experimentally proven through the cloning and characterization of homologs of the *Antirrhinum* genes *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* in a Liliaceae, the tulip *Tulipa gesneriana*.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are expressed in verticils 1,2 and 3.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* have also been isolated and characterized in *Agapanthus praecox* ssp.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] *orientalis* (Agapanthaceae), which is phylogenetically distant from the model organisms.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this study the genes were called *ApGLO* and *ApDEF*, respectively.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both contain open reading frames that code for proteins with 210 to 214 amino acids.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic analysis of these sequences indicated that they belong to B gene family of the monocotyledons.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In situ hybridization studies revealed that both sequences are expressed in verticil 1 as well as in 2 and 3.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] When taken together, these observations show that the floral development mechanism of *Agapanthus* also follows the modified ABC model.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, the C function is derived from one MADS-box type gene called *AGAMOUS* (*AG*), which intervenes both in the establishment of stamen and carpel identity as well as in the determination of the floral meristem.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Therefore, the *AG* mutants are devoid of androecium and gynoecium and they have petals and sepals in their place.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition, the growth in the centre of the flower is undifferentiated, therefore the petals and sepals grow in repetitive verticils.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *PLENA* (*PLE*) gene is present in *A. majus*, in place of the *AG* gene, although it is not an ortholog.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, the *FARINELLI* (*FAR*) gene is an ortholog, which is specific to the development of the anthers and the maturation of pollen.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Petunia*, *Antirrhinum* and in maize the C function is controlled by a number of genes that act in the same manner.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The genes that are closer homologs of *AG* in *Petunia* are *pMADS3* and *floral-binding protein 6* (*FBP6*).
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The D function genes were discovered in 1995.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are MADS-box proteins and they have a function that is distinct from those previously described, although they have a certain homology with C function genes.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are called *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN7* (*FBP7*) and *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN1L* (*FBP1l*).
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was found that, in *Petunia*, they are involved in the development of the ovule.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] Equivalent genes were later found in *Arabidopsis*, where they are also involved in controlling the development of carpels and the ovule and even with structures related to seed dispersal.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The appearance of interesting phenotypes in RNA interference studies in *Petunia* and tomato led, in 1994, to the definition of a new type of function in the floral development model.
[src:embryophyte/abc-model-of-flower-development] The E function was initially thought to be only involved in the development of the three innermost verticils, however, subsequent work found that its expression was required in all the floral verticils.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] Fossils from which the genus was first described were found in the Aberlemno quarry, Scotland.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] Other fossils now assigned to *Aberlemnia caledonica* have been found in Wales, Brazil and possibly Bolivia.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] Plants consisted of smooth leafless stems (axes) up to 1.4 mm wide, decreasing in width at each branching.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] Specimens branched up to five times, at angles between 25 and 55°, mainly dichotomously, although those from Brazil had some trichotomies.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] Spore-forming organs or sporangia were borne at the ends of the stems.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] Smaller ones were more or less circular in outline, larger ones were kidney-shaped (reniform), up to 2 mm high and 3 mm wide.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] The difference in shape is interpreted as being due to growth and maturation.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] To release their spores, the sporangia split into two valves along the border opposite to the stem on which they were attached (i.e. distally).
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] Specimens were first attributed to *Cooksonia caledonica* by Edwards in 1970.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] According to a review of the genus *Cooksonia* by Gonez and Gerrienne, the sporangium of the type species (*C. pertoni*) is formed by a widening of the end of a stem.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] At maturity the sporangium is topped by a flattish disk (an operculum) and releases its spores when this breaks up.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] The sporangia of *C. caledonica* are quite different.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] No existing genus was considered to cover the precise morphology of this plant, so that a new genus *Aberlemnia* was put forward.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] The name is based on the location where the first fossils were found, Aberlemno in Scotland.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] In 2013, Hao and Xue classified *Aberlemnia* as a rhyniopsid, in the subgroup they called "renalioids", along with *Renalia* and *Hsua*.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] Gonez and Gerrienne consider that *Cooksonia* is the most basal of the stem group of the lycophytes, whereas their genus *Aberlemnia* diverged later and is more derived.
[src:embryophyte/aberlemnia] Consistent with this position, the genus has a combination of inherited features or plesiomorphies, such as dichotomous branching and terminal sporangia, with more advanced features, such as bivalved sporangia, which are characteristic of the lycophytes.
[src:embryophyte/acinetactis] The validity and classification of this genus is contested.
[src:embryophyte/acinetactis] In 1914, Adolf Pascher cast doubt on *Acinetactis*, suggesting that it was a junior synonym of *Dimorpha mutans*.
[src:embryophyte/acinetactis] Cavalier-Smith classified *Acinetactis* as a heliomonad in 1993.
[src:embryophyte/acinetactis] Bass et al. suggested in 2009 that the genus was a cercozoan in the class Granofilosea.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] Acritarchs were originally defined as non-acid soluble (i.e. non-carbonate, non-siliceous) organic-walled microfossils consisting of a central cavity, and whose biological affinities cannot be determined with certainty.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] Most commonly they are composed of thermally altered acid-insoluble carbon compounds (kerogen).
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] Acritarchs may include the remains of a wide range of quite different kinds of organisms—ranging from the egg cases of small metazoans to resting cysts of many kinds of chlorophyta (green algae).
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] It is likely that most acritarch species from the Paleozoic represent various stages of the life cycle of algae that were ancestral to the dinoflagellates.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] The nature of the organisms associated with Precambrian acritarchs is generally not well understood, though many are probably related to unicellular marine algae.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] In theory, when the biological source (taxon) of an acritarch does become known, that particular microfossil is removed from the acritarchs and classified with its proper group.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] While the classification of acritarchs into form genera is entirely artificial, it is not without merit, as the form taxa show traits similar to those of genuine taxa—for example an 'explosion' in the Cambrian and a mass extinction at the end of the Permian.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] The informal group Acritarcha Evitt 1963 was originally divided into these Subgroups: Acanthomorphitae, Polygonomorphitae, Prismatomorphitae, Oömorphitae, Netromorphitae, Dinetromorphitae, Stephanomorphitae, Pteromorphitae, Herkomorphitae, Platymorphitae, Sphaeromorphitae, and Disphaeromorphitae.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] In the end, it may well be, as Moczydłowska et al. suggested in 2011, that many acritarchs will, in fact, turn out to be algae.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] Acritarchs are found in sedimentary rocks from the present back into the Archean.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] They are typically isolated from siliciclastic sedimentary rocks using hydrofluoric acid but are occasionally extracted from carbonate-rich rocks.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] They are excellent candidates for index fossils used for dating rock formations in the Paleozoic Era and when other fossils are not available.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] Because most acritarchs are thought to be marine (pre-Triassic), they are also useful for palaeoenvironmental interpretation.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] The Archean and earliest Proterozoic microfossils termed "acritarchs" may actually be prokaryotes.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] The earliest eukaryotic acritarchs known (as of 2020) are from between 1950 and 2150 million years ago.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] At about 1 billion years ago the organisms responsible for acritarchs started to increase in abundance, diversity, size, complexity of shape, and especially, the size and number of spines.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] Their populations crashed during periods of extensive worldwide glaciations that covered the majority of the planet, but they proliferated in the Cambrian explosion and reached their highest diversity in the Paleozoic.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] The increased spininess 1000 million years ago possibly resulted from the need for defense against predators, especially predators large enough to swallow them or tear them apart.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] Other groups of small organisms from the Neoproterozoic era also show signs of anti-predator defenses.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] Further evidence that acritarchs were subject to herbivory around this time comes from a consideration of taxon longevity.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] Approximately 1,000 million years ago, species longevity fell sharply, suggesting that predation pressure, probably by protist herbivores, became an important factor.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] Predation would have kept populations in check, meaning that some nutrients were left unused, and new niches were available for new species to occupy.
[src:embryophyte/acritarch] There are over 900 described genera; the following is a partial list, from Fossilid.info.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] The **actinophryids** are an order of heliozoa, a polyphyletic array of amoebae.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] They are common in fresh water and occasionally found in marine and soil habitats.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Actinophryids are unicellular and roughly spherical in shape, with many axopodia that radiate outward from the cell body.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Axopodia are a type of pseudopodia that are supported by hundreds of microtubules arranged in interlocking spirals and forming a needle-like internal structure or axoneme.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Small granules, extrusomes, that lie under the membrane of the body and axopodia capture flagellates, ciliates and small metazoa that make contact with the arms.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Actinophryids are largely aquatic protozoa with a spherical cell body and many needle-like axopodia.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] They resemble the shape of a sun due to this structure, which is the inspiration for their common name: heliozoa, or "sun-animalcules".
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Their bodies, without arms, range in size from a few tens of micrometers to slightly under a millimeter across.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] The outer region of cell body is often vacuolated.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] The endoplasm of actinophryids is less vacuolated than the outer layer, and a sharp boundary layer may be seen by light microscopy.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] The organisms can be either mononucleate, with a single, well defined nucleus in the center of the cell body, or multinucleate, with 10 or more nuclei located under the outer vacuolated layer of cytoplasm.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] The cytoplasm of actinophryids is often granular, similar to that of *Amoeba*.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Actinophryid cells may fuse when feeding, creating larger aggregated organisms.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Fine granules that occur just under the cell membrane are used up when food vacuoles form to enclose prey.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Actinophryids may also form cysts when food is not readily available.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] A layer of siliceous plates is deposited under the cell membrane during the encystment process.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are common in these organisms, which are presumed to use them to maintain body volume by expelling fluids to compensate for the entry of water by osmosis.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are visible as clear bulges from the surface of the cell body that slowly fill then rapidly deflate, expelling their contents into the environment.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] The most distinctive characteristic of the actinophryids is their axopodia.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] These axopodia consist of a central, rigid rod which is coated in a thin layer of ectoplasm.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] In *Actinophrys* the axonemes end on the surface of the central nucleus, and in the multicellular *Actinosphaerium* they end at or near nuclei.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] The axonemes are composed of microtubules arranged in a double spiral pattern characteristic of the order.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Due to their long, parallel construction, these microtubules demonstrate strong birefringence.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] These axopodia are used for prey capture, in movement, cell fusion and perhaps division.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] They are stiff but may flex especially near their tips, and are highly dynamic, undergoing frequent construction and destruction.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] When used to collect prey items, two methods of capture have been noted, termed axopodial flow and rapid axopodial contraction.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Axopodial flow involves the slow movement of a prey item along the surface of the axopod as the ectoplasm itself moves, while rapid axopodial contraction involves the collapse of the axoneme's microtubule structure.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] This behavior has been documented in many species, including *Actinosphaerium nucleofilum*, *Actinophrys sol*, and *Raphidiophrys contractilis*.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] The rapid axopodial contraction occurs at high speed, often in excess of 5mm/s or tens of body lengths per second.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] The axopodial contractions have been shown to be highly sensitive to environmental factors such as temperature and pressure as well as chemical signals like Ca2+ and colchicine.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Reproduction in actinophryids generally takes place via fission, where one parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] For multinucleate heliozoa, this process is plasmotomic as the nuclei are not duplicated prior to division.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] It has been observed that reproduction appears to be a response to food scarcity, with an increased number of divisions following the removal of food and larger organisms during times of food excess.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Actinophryids also undergo autogamy during times of food scarcity.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] This is better described as genetic reorganization than reproduction, as the number of individuals produced is the same as the initial number.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Nonetheless, it serves as a way to increase genetic diversity within an individual which may improve the likelihood of expressing favorable genetic traits.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Plastogamy has also been extensively documented in actinophryids, especially in multinucleate ones.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* were observed to combine freely without the combination of nuclei, and this process sometimes resulted in more or less individuals than originally combined.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] This process is not caused merely by contact between two individuals but can be caused by damage to the cell body.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Under unfavourable conditions, some species will form a cyst.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] This is often the product of autogamy, in which case the cysts produced are zygotes.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Cells undergoing this process withdraw their axopodia, adhere to the substrate, and take on an opaque and grayish appearance.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] This cyst then divides until only uninucleate cells remain.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] The cyst wall is thickly layered 7–8 times and includes gelatinous layers, layers of silica plates, and iron.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Originally placed in Heliozoa (Sarcodina), the actinophryids are now understood to be part of the stramenopiles.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] They are unrelated to centrohelid and desmothoracid heliozoa with which they had been previously classified.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] There are several genera included within this classification.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] *Actinophrys* are smaller and have a single, central nucleus.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] Most have a cell body 40–50 micrometer in diameter with axopods around 100 μm in length, though this varies significantly.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* are several times larger, from 200 to 1000 μm in diameter, with many nuclei and are found exclusively in fresh water.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] A third genus, *Camptonema*, has a debated status.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] It has been observed once and was treated as a junior subjective synonym of *Actinosphaerium* by Mikrjukov & Patterson in 2001, but as a valid genus by Cavalier-Smith & Scoble (2013).
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] *Heliorapha* is a further debated taxon, it being a new generic vehicle for the species *azurina* that was initially assigned to the genus *Ciliophrys*.
[src:embryophyte/actinophryid] According to the latest review of actinophryid classifications, they are organized into two genera and six species.
[src:embryophyte/adoketophyton] Like other Early Devonian plants, the sporophyte of *Adoketophyton* consisted of leafless stems (axes), approximately 1 to 2.5 mm in diameter.
[src:embryophyte/adoketophyton] These branched equally or unequally (pseudomonopodially).
[src:embryophyte/adoketophyton] Its vascular tissue was relatively simple, consisting of a central (centrarch) cylinder of primary xylem with G-type tracheids.
[src:embryophyte/adoketophyton] Fossils suggest that stems which did not bear sporangia initially had coiled (circinnate) tips, consistent with other "zosterophylls", and similar to the way in which modern ferns grow.
[src:embryophyte/adoketophyton] A unique feature of this genus among plants of similar age is the manner in which the sporangia (spore-forming organs) were borne.
[src:embryophyte/adoketophyton] Fertile stems had terminal 'strobili', structures very superficially resembling an ear of wheat, which consisted of four vertical rows of fan-shaped leaf-like organs (sporophylls), each with a stalked sporangium on the side facing the stem (adaxial).
[src:embryophyte/adoketophyton] The flattened sporangia were almost round and split (dehisced) along a distally thickened margin into two equal parts.
[src:embryophyte/adoketophyton] The sporophylls may have had vascular tissue.
[src:embryophyte/adoketophyton] A second species, *A. parvulum*, was described in 2011.
[src:embryophyte/adoketophyton] The species differ in size overall; for example, the largest strobili found were 90 mm long in *A. subverticillatum*, but only 17 mm long in *A. parvulum*.
[src:embryophyte/adoketophyton] The relative size of the sporophylls and the sporangia is also different: they were roughly the same height in *A. parvulum*, whereas the sporangia were a half to a third of the height of the sporophylls in *A. subverticillatum*.
[src:embryophyte/adoketophyton] A cladogram published in 2004 by Crane et al. places *Adoketophyton* in a paraphyletic stem group of broadly defined "zosterophylls", basal to the lycopsids (living and extinct clubmosses and relatives).
[src:embryophyte/adoketophyton] Other researchers have concluded that the mixture of relatively 'primitive' vascular tissue and 'advanced' sporophylls suggests that the genus evolved separately from the lycopsids, so that its taxonomic placement is uncertain.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] The genus ***Aesculus*** (/ˈaɪskjʊləs/) is a genus of flowering plants in the family Sapindaceae.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] They are trees and shrubs, mostly native to the temperate Northern Hemisphere, but one species (*A. assamica*) into subtropical areas of southeast Asia.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] The Plants of the World Online (POWO) database currently accepts 12 species, with seven species native to North America, four native to Asia, and one native to Europe; some other authors have accepted more species.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] Hardin (1957–1960) accepted 13 species, the *Trees and Shrubs Online* website cites "13–15" species with descriptions given for 14 species, and Harris et al.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] Six natural hybrids occur, and several others have been raised in cultivation.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] The European and Asian species are known as **horse-chestnut** or **horse chestnut**, and the North American species as **buckeye**.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] *Aesculus* exhibits a classical Arcto-Tertiary distribution.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] Carl Linnaeus named the genus *Aesculus* after the Roman name for an edible acorn.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] The genus was considered to be in the ditypic family Hippocastanaceae along with *Billia*, but phylogenetic analyses of morphological and molecular data have more recently caused this family, along with the Aceraceae (maples and *Dipteronia*), to be included in the soapberry family (Sapindaceae).
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] The fruit of the Mexican buckeye resemble *Aesculus* fruit, but belong to a related though different genus *Ungnadia*.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] The common name "horse chestnut" invites confusion with the chestnuts in the genus *Castanea* in the order Fagales; the name is often hyphenated as horse-chestnut to minimise this confusion.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] All parts of the trees are moderately toxic, but the attractive nut-like seeds are the most likely part to cause poisoning.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] The toxin affects the gastrointestinal system, causing gastrointestinal disturbances.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] The USDA notes that the toxicity is due to the saponin aescin and the glucoside aesculin, with alkaloids possibly contributing.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] In North America, several native American tribes, particularly in the western and central United States, such as Miwok, Pomo, Yokut, Maidu, historically used buckeye seeds like California buckeye to harvest fish by using the saponins, which had been extracted by the plant's seeds.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] These tribes would crush buckeye seeds to release saponins into streams or shallow water, where the compounds would stun or kill the fish, allowing for easier capture.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] They then boiled and drained (leached) the fish at least three times to dilute the toxin's effects.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] New shoots from the seeds also have been known to kill grazing cattle.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] In Britain, the fruit are often called **conkers** because of their link to the game of conkers, played with the seeds.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] The most familiar member of the genus worldwide is the common horse-chestnut, *Aesculus hippocastanum*.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] The yellow buckeye, *Aesculus flava* (syn.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] *A. octandra*), is also a valuable ornamental tree with yellow flowers, but is less widely planted.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] Among the smaller species is the bottlebrush buckeye, *Aesculus parviflora*, a flowering shrub.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] Several other members of the genus are used as ornamental plants, and several horticultural hybrids have also been developed, most notably the red horse-chestnut *Aesculus* × *carnea*, a hybrid between *A. hippocastanum* and *A. pavia*.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] The horse-chestnut *A. hippocastanum* was unknown to botanical science until 1596, when the Dutch botanist Carolus Clusius was given foliage and flowers in Vienna; it was then introduced further west, with the first plants reaching France in 1603, and Britain between 1612–1615.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] In Geneva, Switzerland, an official chestnut tree is used to indicate the beginning of the Spring; every year since 1818, the tree is observed by the secretary of the Grand Council of Geneva (the local parliament), and the opening of the first leaf is recorded and announced publicly.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] Over the years, four different horse chestnut trees have been used for these recordings.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] In the 1840 U.S. presidential campaign, candidate William Henry Harrison called himself the "log cabin and hard cider candidate", portraying himself sitting in a log cabin made of buckeye logs and drinking hard cider, causing Ohio to become known as "the Buckeye State".
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] The leaf of *Aesculus* was the official symbol of Kyiv on its coat of arms used from 1969 to 1995.
[src:embryophyte/aesculus] It remains an official symbol of Kyiv to this day.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The **embryophytes** (/ˈɛmbriəˌfaɪts/) are plants of the clade **Embryophyta**, also known as **Plantae *sensu strictissimo*** (/ˌɛmbriˈɒfətə, -oʊˈfaɪtə/, "plant in the strictest sense") or **land plants**.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] They are complex multicellular eukaryotes with haplodiplontic life cycles.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] All have specialized reproductive organs called sporangia, and reproduce sexually via alternation of generations using spores or seeds.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The name "embryophyte" derives from their innovative characteristic of nurturing the embryonic sporophytes within the tissues of the parent gametophytes during the early stages of multicellular development.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] They are the dominant group of autotrophs that make up the vegetation on Earth's terrestrial and wetland ecosystems, and represent the quintessential concept of "plants" most familiar to the common knowledge.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The study of embryophytes is called phytology.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Embryophytes consist of the relatively species-poor non-vascular plants and the much more species-rich vascular plants (tracheophytes).
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Since their boom during the mid/late Cretaceous, angiosperms have been the dominant group of embryophytes.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Embryophytes are predominantly a terrestrial chloroplastidian clade that shared a common ancestry with freshwater green algae, having emerged within the Phragmoplastophyta clade of charophyte algae as a sister clade of Charophyceae, Coleochaetophyceae and Zygnematophyceae.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] With very few exceptions, embryophytes are photoautotrophic and obtain metabolic biological energy by photosynthesis, using chlorophyll a and b to harvest light energy from sunlight for carbon fixation in order to synthesize carbohydrates, while releasing oxygen as a byproduct.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] This primary production is the foundation of terrestrial food webs, where biomass and energy are introduced into the food chain via herbivory and detritivory.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The carbon sequestration by land plants, particularly by the expansive Carboniferous coal forests, were responsible for the Late Paleozoic icehouse and also the proven reserves of coal and coal seam gas that have been important to humanity's energy economy since the Industrial Revolution.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The ancestors of embryophytes diverged from other green algae either a half-billion years ago, at some time in the interval between the mid-Cambrian and early Ordovician, or almost a billion years ago, during the Tonian or Cryogenian.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] They probably emerged from multicellular charophytes, a clade of freshwater green algae similar to extant Klebsormidiophyceae.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Embryophytes are primarily adapted for life on land, although some are secondarily aquatic.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Accordingly, they are often called land plants or terrestrial plants.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] On a microscopic level, the cells of charophytes are broadly similar to those of chlorophyte green algae, but differ in that in cell division the daughter nuclei are separated by a phragmoplast.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] They are eukaryotic, with a cell wall composed of cellulose and plastids surrounded by two membranes.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The latter include chloroplasts, which conduct photosynthesis and store food in the form of starch, and are characteristically pigmented with chlorophylls *a* and *b*, generally giving them a bright green color.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Embryophyte cells also generally have an enlarged central vacuole enclosed by a vacuolar membrane or tonoplast, which maintains cell turgor and keeps the plant rigid.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] In common with all groups of multicellular algae they have a life cycle which involves alternation of generations.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] A multicellular haploid generation with a single set of chromosomes – the gametophyte – produces sperm and eggs which fuse and grow into a diploid multicellular generation with twice the number of chromosomes – the sporophyte which produces haploid spores at maturity.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The spores divide repeatedly by mitosis and grow into a gametophyte, thus completing the cycle.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Embryophytes have two features related to their reproductive cycles which distinguish them from all other plant lineages.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Firstly, their gametophytes produce sperm and eggs in multicellular structures (called "antheridia" and "archegonia"), and fertilization of the ovum takes place within the archegonium rather than in the external environment.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Secondly, the initial stage of development of the fertilized egg (the zygote) into a diploid multicellular sporophyte, takes place within the archegonium where it is both protected and provided with nutrition.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] This second feature is the origin of the term "embryophyte" – the fertilized egg develops into a protected embryo, rather than dispersing as a single cell.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] In the bryophytes the sporophyte remains dependent on the gametophyte, while in all other embryophytes the sporophyte generation is dominant and capable of independent existence.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Embryophytes also differ from algae by having metamers.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Metamers are repeated units of development, in which each unit derives from a single cell, but the resulting product tissue or part is largely the same for each cell.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The whole organism is thus constructed from similar, repeating parts or *metamers*.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Accordingly, these plants are sometimes termed 'metaphytes' and classified as the group Metaphyta (but Haeckel's definition of Metaphyta places some algae in this group).
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The green algae and land plants form a clade, the Viridiplantae.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] According to molecular clock estimates, the Viridiplantae split 1,200 million years ago to 725 million years ago into two clades: chlorophytes and streptophytes.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The chlorophytes, with around 700 genera, were originally marine algae, although some groups have since spread into fresh water.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The streptophyte algae (i.e. excluding the land plants) have around 122 genera; they adapted to fresh water very early in their evolutionary history and have not spread back into marine environments.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Some time during the Ordovician, streptophytes invaded the land and began the evolution of the embryophyte land plants.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The preponderance of molecular evidence as of 2006 suggested that the groups making up the embryophytes are related as shown in the cladogram below (based on Qiu *et al.* 2006 with additional names from Crane *et al.* 2004).
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] An updated phylogeny of Embryophytes based on the work by Novíkov & Barabaš-Krasni 2015 and Hao and Xue 2013 with plant taxon authors from Anderson, Anderson & Cleal 2007 and some additional clade names.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Puttick et al./Nishiyama et al. are used for the basal clades.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The non-vascular land plants, namely the mosses (Bryophyta), hornworts (Anthocerotophyta), and liverworts (Marchantiophyta), are relatively small plants, often confined to environments that are humid or at least seasonally moist.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] They are limited by their reliance on water needed to disperse their gametes; a few are truly aquatic.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Most are tropical, but there are many arctic species.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] They may locally dominate the ground cover in tundra and Arctic–alpine habitats or the epiphyte flora in rain forest habitats.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] They are usually studied together because of their many similarities.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] All three groups share a haploid-dominant (gametophyte) life cycle and unbranched sporophytes (the plant's diploid generation).
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] These traits appear to be common to all early diverging lineages of non-vascular plants on the land.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Their life-cycle is strongly dominated by the haploid gametophyte generation.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The sporophyte remains small and dependent on the parent gametophyte for its entire brief life.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] All other living groups of land plants have a life cycle dominated by the diploid sporophyte generation.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] It is in the diploid sporophyte that vascular tissue develops.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] In some ways, the term "non-vascular" is a misnomer.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Some mosses and liverworts do produce a special type of vascular tissue composed of complex water-conducting cells.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] However, this tissue differs from that of "vascular" plants in that these water-conducting cells are not lignified.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] It is unlikely that the water-conducting cells in mosses are homologous with the vascular tissue in "vascular" plants.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Like the vascular plants, they have differentiated stems, and although these are most often no more than a few centimeters tall, they provide mechanical support.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Most have leaves, although these typically are one cell thick and lack veins.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] They lack true roots or any deep anchoring structures.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Some species grow a filamentous network of horizontal stems, but these have a primary function of mechanical attachment rather than extraction of soil nutrients (Palaeos 2008).
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] During the Silurian and Devonian periods (around 440 to 360 million years ago), plants evolved which possessed true vascular tissue, including cells with walls strengthened by lignin (tracheids).
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Some extinct early plants appear to be between the grade of organization of bryophytes and that of true vascular plants (eutracheophytes).
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Genera such as *Horneophyton* have water-conducting tissue more like that of mosses, but a different life-cycle in which the sporophyte is branched and more developed than the gametophyte.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Genera such as *Rhynia* have a similar life-cycle but have simple tracheids and so are a kind of vascular plant.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] It was assumed that the gametophyte dominant phase seen in bryophytes used to be the ancestral condition in terrestrial plants, and that the sporophyte dominant stage in vascular plants was a derived trait.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] However, the gametophyte and sporophyte stages were probably equally independent from each other, and that the mosses and vascular plants in that case are both derived, and have evolved in opposite directions.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] During the Devonian period, vascular plants diversified and spread to many different land environments.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] In addition to vascular tissues which transport water throughout the body, tracheophytes have an outer layer or cuticle that resists drying out.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The sporophyte is the dominant generation, and in modern species develops leaves, stems and roots, while the gametophyte remains very small.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] All the vascular plants which disperse through spores were once thought to be related (and were often grouped as 'ferns and allies').
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] However, recent research suggests that leaves evolved quite separately in two different lineages.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The lycophytes or lycopodiophytes – modern clubmosses, spikemosses and quillworts – make up less than 1% of living vascular plants.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] They have small leaves, often called 'microphylls' or 'lycophylls', which are borne all along the stems in the clubmosses and spikemosses, and which effectively grow from the base, via an intercalary meristem.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] It is believed that microphylls evolved from outgrowths on stems, such as spines, which later acquired veins (vascular traces).
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Although the living lycophytes are all relatively small and inconspicuous plants, more common in the moist tropics than in temperate regions, during the Carboniferous period tree-like lycophytes (such as *Lepidodendron*) formed huge forests that dominated the landscape.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The euphyllophytes, making up more than 99% of living vascular plant species, have large 'true' leaves (megaphylls), which effectively grow from the sides or the apex, via marginal or apical meristems.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] One theory is that megaphylls evolved from three-dimensional branching systems by first 'planation' – flattening to produce a two dimensional branched structure – and then 'webbing' – tissue growing out between the flattened branches.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Others have questioned whether megaphylls evolved in the same way in different groups.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The ferns and horsetails (the Polypodiophyta) form a clade; they use spores as their main method of dispersal.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Traditionally, whisk ferns and horsetails were historically treated as distinct from 'true' ferns.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Living whisk ferns and horsetails do not have the large leaves (megaphylls) which would be expected of euphyllophytes.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] This has probably resulted from reduction, as evidenced by early fossil horsetails, in which the leaves are broad with branching veins.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Ferns are a large and diverse group, with some 12,000 species.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] A stereotypical fern has broad, much divided leaves, which grow by unrolling.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Seed plants, which first appeared in the fossil record towards the end of the Paleozoic era, reproduce using desiccation-resistant capsules called seeds.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Starting from a plant which disperses by spores, highly complex changes are needed to produce seeds.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The sporophyte has two kinds of spore-forming organs or sporangia.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] One kind, the megasporangium, produces only a single large spore, a megaspore.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] This sporangium is surrounded by sheathing layers or integuments which form the seed coat.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Within the seed coat, the megaspore develops into a tiny gametophyte, which in turn produces one or more egg cells.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Before fertilization, the sporangium and its contents plus its coat is called an ovule; after fertilization a seed.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] In parallel to these developments, the other kind of sporangium, the microsporangium, produces microspores.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] A tiny gametophyte develops inside the wall of a microspore, producing a pollen grain.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Pollen grains can be physically transferred between plants by the wind or animals, most commonly insects.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Pollen grains can also transfer to an ovule of the same plant, either with the same flower or between two flowers of the same plant (self-fertilization).
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] When a pollen grain reaches an ovule, it enters via a microscopic gap in the coat, the micropyle.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] The tiny gametophyte inside the pollen grain then produces sperm cells which move to the egg cell and fertilize it.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Seed plants include two clades with living members, the gymnosperms and the angiosperms or flowering plants.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] In gymnosperms, the ovules or seeds are not further enclosed.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] In angiosperms, they are enclosed within the carpel.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Angiosperms typically also have other, secondary structures, such as petals, which together form a flower.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Meiosis in sexual land plants provides a direct mechanism for repairing DNA in reproductive tissues.
[src:embryophyte/embryophyte] Sexual reproduction appears to be needed for maintaining long-term genomic integrity and only infrequent combinations of extrinsic and intrinsic factors allow for shifts to asexuality.
